1
00:00:22,887 --> 00:00:25,591
BOY: I want to get a good picture,

2
00:00:27,263 --> 00:00:29,881
some more pictures.

3
00:00:34,013 --> 00:00:37,045
This is Carey's room, her bed.

4
00:00:37,930 --> 00:00:44,257
This is the birthday girl's mattress
and everything else.

5
00:00:44,304 --> 00:00:45,678
She's even got a TV

6
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:46,999
in her room.

7
00:00:47,053 --> 00:00:48,332
Ain't she lucky?

8
00:00:49,512 --> 00:00:51,632
That's my sister.

9
00:00:54,428 --> 00:00:56,052
The birthday girl.

10
00:00:56,930 --> 00:00:58,967
Ain't she beautiful?

11
00:00:59,512 --> 00:01:02,343
And here is her brother.

12
00:01:02,385 --> 00:01:03,795
Nick.

13
00:01:18,136 --> 00:01:21,916
WOMAN: The thought of what somebody
could have done to him...

14
00:01:23,679 --> 00:01:25,337
It gives you nightmares.

15
00:01:27,637 --> 00:01:29,175
It really does.

16
00:01:34,178 --> 00:01:37,092
ANOTHER WOMAN:
His disappearance never made the news.

17
00:01:37,385 --> 00:01:39,211
It wasn't news to them,

18
00:01:41,762 --> 00:01:43,966
it was just news to us.

19
00:01:53,178 --> 00:01:58,461
It came to the point where, you know,
you're not gonna find him alive,

20
00:01:58,510 --> 00:02:01,757
but you just want to
find what happened to him.

21
00:02:02,552 --> 00:02:04,589
(Pouring rain)

22
00:02:49,844 --> 00:02:53,256
MOTHER:
They called me at work when I wasn't there

23
00:02:53,302 --> 00:02:59,298
and they wrote a message and said,
"Someone from Spain has Nicholas."

24
00:03:00,050 --> 00:03:02,171
He wants to come home.

25
00:03:02,217 --> 00:03:03,543
My mom called me.

26
00:03:03,591 --> 00:03:05,417
I was at work.

27
00:03:05,467 --> 00:03:06,711
And she says, "Sitting down?

28
00:03:06,759 --> 00:03:08,300
You're not going to believe this."

29
00:03:08,343 --> 00:03:11,542
Course. It was mysterious,

30
00:03:11,592 --> 00:03:13,915
it was er...exciting,

31
00:03:14,009 --> 00:03:15,417
it was worrisome,

32
00:03:15,467 --> 00:03:18,834
er, it was all mixed emotions, you know?

33
00:03:18,885 --> 00:03:20,543
Ecstatic.

34
00:03:20,593 --> 00:03:22,335
Bewildered.

35
00:03:22,385 --> 00:03:23,546
You know, Spain!

36
00:03:23,593 --> 00:03:25,297
Isn't that like across the country?

37
00:03:25,341 --> 00:03:27,627
Um, how did he get there?

38
00:03:27,674 --> 00:03:30,757
You want...
you have like a hundred thousand questions

39
00:03:30,842 --> 00:03:32,582
that you want answered immediately.

40
00:03:32,674 --> 00:03:35,424
I felt wonderful,

41
00:03:36,883 --> 00:03:39,041
you know, excited.

42
00:03:39,510 --> 00:03:43,336
You wanna see him, touch him,
you know what I mean?

43
00:03:43,383 --> 00:03:46,416
And you want it all to happen now.

44
00:04:10,425 --> 00:04:11,668
(Pouring rain)

45
00:05:06,466 --> 00:05:10,588
From as long as I remember,
I wanted to be someone else.

46
00:05:11,964 --> 00:05:14,120
Someone who was acceptable.

47
00:05:20,006 --> 00:05:21,463
(Siren)

48
00:05:27,297 --> 00:05:31,243
The most important thing for me and what
I learned very fast was to be convincing.

49
00:05:37,048 --> 00:05:38,588
When the police arrive,

50
00:05:38,630 --> 00:05:40,705
I have immediately to put into their mind

51
00:05:40,756 --> 00:05:43,125
they have a kid in front of them,
not an adult.

52
00:05:43,172 --> 00:05:46,206
So it was very important for me
to behave like one.

53
00:05:46,256 --> 00:05:48,460
(Communications over police radio)

54
00:06:03,590 --> 00:06:04,964
(Speaks Spanish)

55
00:06:06,589 --> 00:06:10,119
(Continues to speak Spanish)

56
00:06:10,172 --> 00:06:14,119
They would see me with...
in a big coat with younger clothes.

57
00:06:14,506 --> 00:06:18,879
And they would see a kid with a hat,
which is very low in the eyes.

58
00:06:18,922 --> 00:06:20,200
They couldn't see my eyes.

59
00:06:21,546 --> 00:06:23,833
(Speaks Spanish)

60
00:06:25,838 --> 00:06:28,588
I wanted to provoke on them
a sense of guilt...

61
00:06:30,462 --> 00:06:32,999
(Speaks Spanish)

62
00:06:33,047 --> 00:06:37,503
..of being adults and to be close to a kid
which is dead scared.

63
00:06:38,587 --> 00:06:41,955
When you see a kid that,
you know, got nervous reflexes,

64
00:06:42,006 --> 00:06:44,837
that you can't touch them,
you can't approach them,

65
00:06:44,880 --> 00:06:48,292
then you understand, you understand
that something is wrong.

66
00:06:48,338 --> 00:06:50,493
(Speaks Spanish)

67
00:06:53,755 --> 00:06:55,957
(Speaks Spanish)

68
00:07:04,963 --> 00:07:08,659
I wasn't the one who was telling them
I've been sexually abused.

69
00:07:08,712 --> 00:07:11,960
I made them ask me that by my attitude,

70
00:07:12,004 --> 00:07:13,876
by my way of doing things.

71
00:07:13,921 --> 00:07:17,168
They were the one thinking about it
and that gave me power.

72
00:07:38,545 --> 00:07:40,287
I didn't speak much.

73
00:07:41,921 --> 00:07:44,290
(Woman speaks Spanish)

74
00:07:44,336 --> 00:07:50,533
It's very hard to read a kid
that doesn't speak a word sometime.

75
00:07:54,043 --> 00:07:55,620
(Speaks Spanish)

76
00:07:57,879 --> 00:07:59,869
(Speaks Spanish)

77
00:07:59,920 --> 00:08:02,586
If a cop don't know who a kid is
and where he comes from,

78
00:08:02,627 --> 00:08:04,914
he just can't keep him
in the police station.

79
00:08:06,544 --> 00:08:11,286
And I knew that eventually they would
have to put me into a children's home...

80
00:08:11,337 --> 00:08:13,078
(Speaks Spanish)

81
00:08:13,129 --> 00:08:15,875
..and that's all I wanted.

82
00:08:34,253 --> 00:08:36,539
Nobody ever gave a damn about me

83
00:08:36,586 --> 00:08:41,242
and to know that if I change my identity

84
00:08:41,293 --> 00:08:43,865
the reward was eventually
to be put in a place

85
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:46,288
where actually
they really cared about me...

86
00:08:46,834 --> 00:08:50,331
then, hell, yeah.
I mean, I was reborn.

87
00:08:50,376 --> 00:08:52,367
I mean... (Laughs) ..I was born again.

88
00:08:56,626 --> 00:08:58,168
Nobody ever gave me a childhood,

89
00:08:58,211 --> 00:09:01,658
because to give a kid a childhood
you need to, to love that kid.

90
00:09:08,669 --> 00:09:10,660
I felt like I belonged there.

91
00:09:14,293 --> 00:09:16,450
(Speaks Spanish)

92
00:09:17,583 --> 00:09:22,206
They didn't know
that I was 23, 23 years old.

93
00:09:24,376 --> 00:09:26,783
I was considered like one of them.

94
00:09:45,751 --> 00:09:47,658
BEVERLY: I told him to be home by dinner

95
00:09:47,709 --> 00:09:51,288
and gave him five bucks
to go play basketball,

96
00:09:51,333 --> 00:09:53,490
and... he took off.

97
00:09:56,251 --> 00:09:59,830
He called home, asking for a ride, er...

98
00:09:59,876 --> 00:10:01,665
which was probably, I don't know,

99
00:10:01,709 --> 00:10:04,161
he's within a couple of miles
from his house

100
00:10:04,208 --> 00:10:09,080
and his mother works late
and sleeps during the day

101
00:10:09,125 --> 00:10:14,494
and his older brother Jason
answered the phone.

102
00:10:14,542 --> 00:10:20,538
When I woke up Jason was there and said
that he had called and wanted a ride home,

103
00:10:20,583 --> 00:10:22,739
but Jason didn't want to wake me up,

104
00:10:23,708 --> 00:10:26,115
so told him he had to walk home.

105
00:10:28,209 --> 00:10:34,371
And that's...was the day,
the last time we heard from him.

106
00:10:36,917 --> 00:10:42,071
You spend 24 hours crying, sick, worried,

107
00:10:42,957 --> 00:10:45,790
then you get mad, then you get scared,

108
00:10:45,874 --> 00:10:48,658
and then you try to get empowered.
You know, "OK, what can we do?

109
00:10:48,707 --> 00:10:50,781
We have to do flyers,
we'll do this, we'll..."

110
00:10:50,874 --> 00:10:52,202
You know, so instead of...

111
00:10:52,249 --> 00:10:57,535
you don't cry, you do something positive

112
00:10:57,583 --> 00:11:01,078
and try to work towards, I guess,
a solution of finding him.

113
00:11:03,709 --> 00:11:07,571
BEVERLY: I thought somebody offered him
a ride, and he got in the car.

114
00:11:10,415 --> 00:11:14,077
I dunno, I think he would have got in a car
with someone that he didn't know.

115
00:11:20,956 --> 00:11:23,079
What are you looking at?

116
00:11:24,375 --> 00:11:27,988
I could see the worry and the pain
they were going through,

117
00:11:28,040 --> 00:11:31,903
so I always said, you know,
"He's out there," you know.

118
00:11:31,957 --> 00:11:33,664
"He'll resurface," you know.

119
00:11:48,663 --> 00:11:54,946
Unfortunately for me, it was one of
those places which is very rare in Spain

120
00:11:55,040 --> 00:11:59,530
where actually they can't stand
having a kid with no identity card,

121
00:11:59,580 --> 00:12:01,738
er, no proof of who he is.

122
00:12:01,791 --> 00:12:03,994
(Woman speaks Spanish)

123
00:12:08,747 --> 00:12:12,657
They wanted absolutely to know who I was,
where do I come from,

124
00:12:12,706 --> 00:12:15,324
erm, they needed to know precise.

125
00:12:15,372 --> 00:12:18,156
(Woman continues in Spanish)

126
00:12:19,621 --> 00:12:22,870
"If you don't tell us,
if can't prove us who you are,

127
00:12:22,915 --> 00:12:25,698
I'm gonna have you fingerprinted
and your pictures taken."

128
00:12:27,455 --> 00:12:29,611
I couldn't allow that to happen.

129
00:12:29,663 --> 00:12:32,199
I had to find a way out of that.

130
00:12:32,247 --> 00:12:35,494
So the only, only thing left there was

131
00:12:35,539 --> 00:12:37,694
was 1) go to prison

132
00:12:37,954 --> 00:12:42,080
2) prove to them that I'm someone.

133
00:12:51,872 --> 00:12:54,027
I said that I was American.

134
00:12:54,872 --> 00:13:00,703
That er...I ran away and I was
willing to contact my family for them

135
00:13:00,747 --> 00:13:02,987
but I wanted to do it myself.

136
00:13:05,913 --> 00:13:09,493
I didn't want my family to receive a phone call
from the police or the persecutor

137
00:13:09,538 --> 00:13:11,244
or the judge in Spain.

138
00:13:11,288 --> 00:13:12,745
I wanted to do it myself.

139
00:13:13,663 --> 00:13:16,411
And I said I would need to be
in the office for the night

140
00:13:16,454 --> 00:13:17,947
because I live in the States.

141
00:13:17,996 --> 00:13:21,693
The States is, you know,
the times is different, it's er...

142
00:13:21,746 --> 00:13:25,112
So erm, you know,
just leave me in the office

143
00:13:25,162 --> 00:13:27,154
and tomorrow you will have all you need.

144
00:13:38,371 --> 00:13:39,744
(Speaks Spanish)

145
00:13:47,914 --> 00:13:50,069
In this office nobody could hear me.

146
00:13:51,954 --> 00:13:55,614
I knew that I could pass myself
for anyone on the phone,

147
00:13:55,661 --> 00:13:57,286
could convince anyone of anything.

148
00:14:09,370 --> 00:14:11,242
So I call the American Police.

149
00:14:11,286 --> 00:14:12,743
(Phone rings)

150
00:14:12,786 --> 00:14:14,575
County South, Detective Fowler.

151
00:14:14,619 --> 00:14:15,697
The New York Police.

152
00:14:17,621 --> 00:14:19,078
Lieutenant Kojak's office.

153
00:14:19,454 --> 00:14:21,905
Different police stations in the States.

154
00:14:22,244 --> 00:14:24,069
- Dobie here.
- Who is this, please?

155
00:14:24,120 --> 00:14:26,787
I told them every time
that I was a policeman from Spain

156
00:14:26,870 --> 00:14:29,074
called Jonathan Dorian,

157
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:30,910
that we had found a kid,

158
00:14:31,744 --> 00:14:34,944
we are sure he's from the States
but we don't know where.

159
00:14:34,994 --> 00:14:36,191
How long ago was this?

160
00:14:36,244 --> 00:14:40,866
He's been maybe missing for a few years,
that someone must be looking for him.

161
00:14:41,953 --> 00:14:44,489
So the police say, well, you know,

162
00:14:44,536 --> 00:14:47,867
we got hundreds of posters
of missing persons on the wall

163
00:14:47,912 --> 00:14:50,197
and we just can't go through each of them.

164
00:14:50,245 --> 00:14:51,986
But what we can do for you

165
00:14:52,036 --> 00:14:55,864
is to give you the number of the centre
for missing and exploited children

166
00:14:55,911 --> 00:14:57,451
of Arlington, Virginia.

167
00:15:04,785 --> 00:15:08,696
Centre for missing and exploited children.
Lorraine speaking. How may I help you?

168
00:15:10,660 --> 00:15:14,608
Er, we have a kid in a shelter,
certainly is American,

169
00:15:14,662 --> 00:15:16,652
who is about 14, 15 years old

170
00:15:16,703 --> 00:15:19,107
but the problem is
we don't know who he is...

171
00:15:19,160 --> 00:15:20,570
I describe myself.

172
00:15:20,619 --> 00:15:24,280
Every detail I gave was details
that I know that I could handle.

173
00:15:24,952 --> 00:15:28,613
I wanted to be vague enough for her
to look at many different things.

174
00:15:28,660 --> 00:15:31,230
I wanted her to have many possibilities.

175
00:15:31,284 --> 00:15:32,563
Let me just take a look here.

176
00:15:32,617 --> 00:15:34,526
"I got maybe something," she said.

177
00:15:34,577 --> 00:15:38,736
"Maybe, you know,
we got a kid from San Antonio

178
00:15:38,785 --> 00:15:41,984
missing since June 13 1994.

179
00:15:42,034 --> 00:15:44,323
His name is Nicholas Barclay."

180
00:15:44,369 --> 00:15:47,531
I said, "Could you send me a fax
of what he looks like?"

181
00:15:49,326 --> 00:15:54,529
In my head, I was just a police officer
with, with Nicholas Barclay next to me,

182
00:15:54,576 --> 00:15:59,364
trying to confirm his identity
and like any other policeman would do.

183
00:16:01,950 --> 00:16:04,155
Let's see if it's him.

184
00:16:05,493 --> 00:16:07,530
I thought, let's see if it's him.

185
00:16:15,909 --> 00:16:19,653
I look at it, black and white picture,
old picture.

186
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:24,359
Well, missing for three or four years,

187
00:16:24,409 --> 00:16:27,609
guarantee one thing,
there will be a change.

188
00:16:28,534 --> 00:16:30,440
If there is a change, there will be doubt.

189
00:16:30,491 --> 00:16:33,063
If there is doubt, then I got a chance.

190
00:16:35,449 --> 00:16:41,614
Something in my head decided
I could do it, that I had to try.

191
00:16:47,658 --> 00:16:52,612
I took the phone and I told her
that this is Nicholas.

192
00:16:52,659 --> 00:16:54,565
We got him, it's him.

193
00:16:54,616 --> 00:16:56,654
It's incredible, it's him.

194
00:17:10,743 --> 00:17:13,693
My mom called me
and she says, "Are you sitting down?

195
00:17:13,741 --> 00:17:15,778
You're not gonna believe this."

196
00:17:15,866 --> 00:17:19,029
And I said, "What, Mom?" She goes,
"The police department called me

197
00:17:19,074 --> 00:17:22,238
and they think they found Nicholas
in Linares."

198
00:17:22,283 --> 00:17:25,400
So I'm like, "OK,
where in Texas is Linares?"

199
00:17:25,449 --> 00:17:27,653
Because Texas has a lot of small towns.

200
00:17:27,865 --> 00:17:29,736
And then she was like, "No, Spain."

201
00:17:29,781 --> 00:17:31,109
I'm like, "Spain?"

202
00:17:34,574 --> 00:17:36,730
Oh, God, how to explain the emotions.

203
00:17:37,573 --> 00:17:41,190
It's like all these different emotions,
from excitement to bewilderment,

204
00:17:41,242 --> 00:17:43,195
to what do we do?

205
00:17:43,240 --> 00:17:47,186
What's the next step? How do we get him?
When do we get to talk to him?

206
00:17:49,491 --> 00:17:52,442
I knew that after that
they would contact me.

207
00:17:52,492 --> 00:17:57,111
They would try to verify, to call,
to see, to... Is it true? Is it here?

208
00:17:57,156 --> 00:17:59,396
Is it, you know...
Carey, the family and all that.

209
00:18:00,198 --> 00:18:02,354
(Ringing tone)

210
00:18:09,450 --> 00:18:12,529
Well, when I first got, you know,
got a hold of the shelter,

211
00:18:12,573 --> 00:18:15,654
they put me on the phone
with Jonathan Dorian

212
00:18:15,699 --> 00:18:18,780
who said that he worked
for the, a shelter,

213
00:18:18,866 --> 00:18:22,361
and that he was the one
who was talking with Nicholas

214
00:18:22,407 --> 00:18:26,102
and had got the information from Nicholas
on who he really was.

215
00:18:29,198 --> 00:18:33,109
When she called, I said that Nicholas
was seated next to me.

216
00:18:33,157 --> 00:18:36,687
But he was very scared,
he was very traumatised

217
00:18:36,740 --> 00:18:38,482
and he didn't want to talk to no-one.

218
00:18:38,532 --> 00:18:41,197
He sounded very responsible,
very concerned.

219
00:18:41,239 --> 00:18:44,935
Er, he claims that he has been abused,
that he's been hurt,

220
00:18:44,989 --> 00:18:48,236
that erm...certainly he's been abducted.

221
00:18:48,281 --> 00:18:52,061
I kind of thought he was like
a social worker type of person.

222
00:18:52,115 --> 00:18:54,685
Um, very reassuring.

223
00:18:55,072 --> 00:18:57,277
She said, "Is he saying anything?

224
00:18:57,323 --> 00:18:59,527
Is he talking about us? Does he remember?"

225
00:18:59,573 --> 00:19:03,019
Well, actually, I think he forgot
about everything, you know.

226
00:19:03,071 --> 00:19:04,943
He doesn't remember very much.

227
00:19:04,988 --> 00:19:07,277
He remember you but not very much.

228
00:19:07,324 --> 00:19:12,690
We were told he was held by
some kind of like a sex slave kind of ring,

229
00:19:12,738 --> 00:19:18,320
and that he had escaped from there and
that he was found wandering the streets.

230
00:19:18,364 --> 00:19:21,481
She was heartbroken
but at the same time she was very happy.

231
00:19:21,531 --> 00:19:23,188
I wanted to hear his voice.

232
00:19:23,239 --> 00:19:24,611
No!

233
00:19:24,654 --> 00:19:29,277
Absolutely, there was no way I was going
to talk to her pretending to be Nicholas

234
00:19:29,322 --> 00:19:32,983
because I wasn't Nicholas
and she was his sister,

235
00:19:33,029 --> 00:19:36,527
so er...it would have been a risk,

236
00:19:36,573 --> 00:19:38,444
too big a risk for me,

237
00:19:38,490 --> 00:19:40,360
but I did say a few words.

238
00:19:41,571 --> 00:19:44,569
She said: "Hello, Nicholas.
You hear me, Nicholas?"

239
00:19:47,113 --> 00:19:49,187
Nothing.

240
00:19:49,738 --> 00:19:52,937
"I love you, Nicholas.
I want to take you back home with me.

241
00:19:52,988 --> 00:19:54,266
I'm gonna take you, baby.

242
00:19:54,320 --> 00:19:56,396
I'm gonna come and get you and..."

243
00:19:59,196 --> 00:20:04,185
And maybe you hear "Love you"
or something like that, you know.

244
00:20:04,697 --> 00:20:06,238
Very far away. It, it...

245
00:20:06,280 --> 00:20:08,234
And then she say: "Was it him?"

246
00:20:08,279 --> 00:20:10,150
I said, "Yeah. He said 'I love you."'

247
00:20:10,446 --> 00:20:12,567
Oh. And then she started crying
on the phone.

248
00:20:13,904 --> 00:20:18,526
You start crying, you tell him, "We're
going to come and get you, bring you home.

249
00:20:18,571 --> 00:20:21,983
We'll get there, we're going to bring
you home, and I love you too."

250
00:20:24,987 --> 00:20:27,688
I erm... I washed her brain.

251
00:20:43,737 --> 00:20:48,193
I didn't stop,
because I didn't think of stopping.

252
00:20:49,486 --> 00:20:53,480
I didn't watch myself in the mirror
and say, "What the fuck are you doing?

253
00:20:53,528 --> 00:20:55,602
Stop that immediately."

254
00:21:01,987 --> 00:21:04,061
(Footsteps)

255
00:21:04,404 --> 00:21:08,266
I realised that I've crossed the line.

256
00:21:09,986 --> 00:21:15,320
I wasn't pretending no more
to have another identity. I stole one.

257
00:21:26,194 --> 00:21:27,474
(Phone rings)

258
00:21:30,777 --> 00:21:34,523
I got a phone call: "Would you please
call a Carey Gibson?"

259
00:21:36,945 --> 00:21:39,183
Well, I was astounded by what Carey said,

260
00:21:41,485 --> 00:21:45,146
so one of the first things I said to her was,

261
00:21:45,193 --> 00:21:49,731
when the FBI
and the US State Department assist you

262
00:21:49,775 --> 00:21:55,192
and uh...get you and your brother back here,
I have to interview him immediately.

263
00:22:02,404 --> 00:22:05,068
When the welfare of a minor,

264
00:22:05,110 --> 00:22:06,732
er...is in jeopardy,

265
00:22:07,235 --> 00:22:09,854
our reaction has to be very quick,

266
00:22:09,902 --> 00:22:11,525
er...very responsive.

267
00:22:11,568 --> 00:22:12,812
We have to put ourselves

268
00:22:12,860 --> 00:22:14,103
in the position of the child

269
00:22:14,151 --> 00:22:16,225
or the child's parents or guardians.

270
00:22:16,902 --> 00:22:20,183
Generally when a child is missing for years,

271
00:22:20,233 --> 00:22:25,437
either the child is dead or the child is not found

272
00:22:25,485 --> 00:22:30,438
and to find that child in another country
is extremely rare.

273
00:22:30,902 --> 00:22:34,017
That made it all the more compelling for us

274
00:22:34,067 --> 00:22:37,896
to make sure that we did everything right
in terms of er...

275
00:22:37,942 --> 00:22:41,107
establishing who he was
and getting him back to his family.

276
00:22:41,152 --> 00:22:43,106
My main concern was getting him back,

277
00:22:43,150 --> 00:22:46,848
so that my part could start,
the investigation could start...

278
00:22:46,984 --> 00:22:49,390
we could find out
what had happened to this child.

279
00:22:49,443 --> 00:22:51,598
I sent somebody out there
as quickly as possible.

280
00:23:02,359 --> 00:23:04,929
The next day...
The next day, it got beyond my control.

281
00:23:06,900 --> 00:23:10,431
The centre for missing
and exploited children sent me a flyer.

282
00:23:11,235 --> 00:23:14,598
There was the picture of Nicholas
at the time of his disappearance...

283
00:23:18,650 --> 00:23:23,272
And I saw what real Nicholas looked like,
really with colours and everything.

284
00:23:26,274 --> 00:23:28,515
He was very blond, very...

285
00:23:28,567 --> 00:23:30,891
He had blue eyes.

286
00:23:30,943 --> 00:23:32,980
He looked nothing like me!

287
00:23:33,524 --> 00:23:34,722
Nothing!

288
00:23:34,775 --> 00:23:37,892
There's, you know, the only thing
he had in common with me

289
00:23:37,942 --> 00:23:40,312
was that he had five fingers
at each hands.

290
00:23:42,066 --> 00:23:44,389
Then I said, fuck, let's burn myself.

291
00:23:45,232 --> 00:23:47,138
You know, I burned the flyer.

292
00:23:47,189 --> 00:23:49,347
If I could have burned the identity that I said

293
00:23:49,399 --> 00:23:52,148
and every word that had been
out of my mouth for the past few days,

294
00:23:52,190 --> 00:23:53,932
I would have burned them too!

295
00:24:00,774 --> 00:24:04,767
When everyone tells me
that the American Embassy is coming

296
00:24:04,815 --> 00:24:07,518
and er...everybody's, you know...

297
00:24:07,566 --> 00:24:10,137
and don't worry, Nicholas,
we're gonna take care of you.

298
00:24:10,191 --> 00:24:15,427
Well, yeah, OK,
you know, I... I couldn't do nothing.

299
00:24:15,898 --> 00:24:17,225
The only thing I could do

300
00:24:17,274 --> 00:24:20,555
was think of how was going to be the prison
where I was going to be.

301
00:24:30,357 --> 00:24:31,730
I didn't know what to do.

302
00:24:31,773 --> 00:24:33,810
I really didn't know what to do.

303
00:24:35,231 --> 00:24:38,016
When the Vice Consul
first arrived in Linares,

304
00:24:38,065 --> 00:24:41,147
he got to the centre and found
Nicholas Barclay had disappeared.

305
00:24:47,439 --> 00:24:49,014
I said, you've got to find him.

306
00:24:50,649 --> 00:24:54,724
So he essentially,
with somebody from the Linares Centre,

307
00:24:54,773 --> 00:24:56,894
went around looking for him.

308
00:24:58,025 --> 00:25:02,397
Our priority was his safety and to make sure
he was reunited with the family.

309
00:25:06,316 --> 00:25:09,811
I tried to run away
like I would do anywhere else.

310
00:25:16,147 --> 00:25:17,605
Nicholas Barclay?

311
00:25:18,397 --> 00:25:20,471
God didn't want me to leave this place.

312
00:25:20,939 --> 00:25:25,016
I spoke with the vice consul and asked him
about his interactions with Nicholas.

313
00:25:25,065 --> 00:25:29,058
He reported at the time
that he spoke English,

314
00:25:29,606 --> 00:25:34,429
that he, he was,
he was at least at that moment

315
00:25:34,481 --> 00:25:36,222
convinced that this was an American.

316
00:25:44,814 --> 00:25:47,764
When I woke up the next morning,
everything was normal.

317
00:25:47,813 --> 00:25:49,603
(Knock at door)

318
00:25:52,897 --> 00:25:56,062
Then I saw the director of the shelter
that said,

319
00:25:56,107 --> 00:25:59,552
"Well, you know, you must be happy,
your sister is on the way."

320
00:26:00,146 --> 00:26:02,517
So I said, "What do you mean?"

321
00:26:02,563 --> 00:26:07,055
He say, "Well, your sister,
you know, from San Antonio,

322
00:26:07,105 --> 00:26:09,640
she's on the plane,
she's coming to get you."

323
00:26:12,520 --> 00:26:14,014
Fuck, you know. Fuck! Fuck!

324
00:26:14,063 --> 00:26:15,260
Fuck! Fuck! Fuck!

325
00:26:15,313 --> 00:26:16,935
I'd never left the country.

326
00:26:16,979 --> 00:26:19,550
I didn't know even what it entailed.

327
00:26:24,314 --> 00:26:26,102
I knew Mom couldn't handle the flight.

328
00:26:26,146 --> 00:26:27,639
She can't, she couldn't do it.

329
00:26:27,688 --> 00:26:29,097
I have to do this.

330
00:26:29,146 --> 00:26:32,429
I just gotta go get him
and get him back here where he's safe.

331
00:26:35,938 --> 00:26:37,809
I should have thought of that.

332
00:26:39,021 --> 00:26:41,306
I should have thought of the consequences.

333
00:26:41,352 --> 00:26:43,427
If you do that, imagine for a second

334
00:26:43,478 --> 00:26:48,017
that you're the father of a kid that's
been missing for three years, four months,

335
00:26:48,062 --> 00:26:51,476
and that they find him in Columbia,
er...what would you do?

336
00:26:51,605 --> 00:26:53,512
What would be the first thing you'd do?

337
00:26:54,021 --> 00:26:56,095
I would jump on a fucking plane.

338
00:26:58,688 --> 00:27:01,768
I didn't sleep for two days
before I got on the plane.

339
00:27:01,812 --> 00:27:04,928
Fear, but also anticipation,

340
00:27:05,312 --> 00:27:07,018
cos you want to get there, get there.

341
00:27:07,062 --> 00:27:10,807
You want to see him, hold him,
smell him, just get there.

342
00:27:11,520 --> 00:27:16,223
You can't prepare to play a role
of a person that you don't know.

343
00:27:17,603 --> 00:27:21,266
I couldn't be Nicholas Barclay
because I didn't know Nicholas Barclay.

344
00:27:21,938 --> 00:27:24,969
I didn't even know at that moment
if he was left or right-handed.

345
00:27:25,604 --> 00:27:28,635
So, er, that was a problem.

346
00:27:29,394 --> 00:27:32,926
I got on the plane and tried to sleep.

347
00:27:32,978 --> 00:27:34,684
Didn't work.

348
00:27:53,560 --> 00:27:55,634
(Nick's voice)

349
00:27:56,687 --> 00:27:58,760
The director...

350
00:28:02,186 --> 00:28:04,804
This is Nick, mwhah.

351
00:28:11,269 --> 00:28:12,926
BEVERLY: He thought he was an adult.

352
00:28:12,976 --> 00:28:16,094
We called him 13 going on 30.

353
00:28:16,935 --> 00:28:19,389
Very difficult to discipline him.

354
00:28:20,186 --> 00:28:23,433
If he made up his mind
he was gonna do something,

355
00:28:23,478 --> 00:28:26,557
pretty much there wasn't a lot you could do.

356
00:28:27,977 --> 00:28:30,051
Put the lighter down.

357
00:28:31,436 --> 00:28:34,350
CAREY: He'd run away before
for a night or two, mad at Mom.

358
00:28:34,394 --> 00:28:36,798
"I'm leaving, I'll find a new mom, a new home.

359
00:28:36,892 --> 00:28:38,635
Kiss my ass," kind of thing.

360
00:28:38,685 --> 00:28:42,595
And he, you know... would leave
and she would hunt him down

361
00:28:42,643 --> 00:28:45,758
and find out where he is
and he'd show up the next day.

362
00:28:46,769 --> 00:28:52,800
He was not, um, you know,
this perfect nice sweet innocent,

363
00:28:52,893 --> 00:28:56,389
he was a very street-smart city boy.

364
00:28:59,518 --> 00:29:04,590
- It's nice to meet ya. I am the director.
- In here, Nick.

365
00:29:04,643 --> 00:29:06,715
See, ain't I beautiful?

366
00:29:07,101 --> 00:29:09,767
He had beautiful blond hair.

367
00:29:09,809 --> 00:29:12,592
Kind of looked like, erm, a little pixie.

368
00:29:13,142 --> 00:29:16,390
He had blond hair and blue eyes
and a bit of a gap between his teeth.

369
00:29:16,436 --> 00:29:18,508
When he smiled, you could see it.

370
00:29:43,058 --> 00:29:46,971
Finally I'm on the ground.
"Who, who, who am I looking for?

371
00:29:47,019 --> 00:29:48,971
What do they look like? Are they in suits?

372
00:29:49,017 --> 00:29:50,972
Oh, damn, you can smoke here. Thank God!"

373
00:29:53,224 --> 00:29:54,552
The air smelt different.

374
00:29:54,600 --> 00:29:57,765
Erm,
it was a lot less crowded than I thought.

375
00:30:07,766 --> 00:30:12,008
I did everything I could
to give myself a chance.

376
00:30:16,143 --> 00:30:20,383
I bought product to colour my hair totally blond.

377
00:30:23,433 --> 00:30:25,555
The gentlemen and a lady approached me,

378
00:30:25,600 --> 00:30:27,970
cos I wasn't sure where to go

379
00:30:28,016 --> 00:30:30,587
and we went straight into a car
and started driving.

380
00:30:35,890 --> 00:30:39,587
On the flyers it said that Nicholas Barclay
had three tattoos.

381
00:30:42,390 --> 00:30:46,764
There was a girl inside the shelter
that did small tattoos just like that.

382
00:30:46,808 --> 00:30:48,798
She was no pro, she was just a kid.

383
00:30:49,057 --> 00:30:50,965
And I asked her to put those tattoos

384
00:30:51,016 --> 00:30:52,923
that were on the flyers on me.

385
00:31:01,472 --> 00:31:06,261
I was quiet and that's when
the lady started talking to me.

386
00:31:08,224 --> 00:31:12,799
She kept my mind busy
with explaining the countryside to me

387
00:31:12,891 --> 00:31:14,965
the whole way down there on the drive.

388
00:31:18,889 --> 00:31:25,385
I took big sunglasses, I took a hat,
I took a scarf, I took a glove.

389
00:31:25,891 --> 00:31:27,679
I thought that if she couldn't see me,

390
00:31:27,723 --> 00:31:30,505
then she wouldn't be able to say
I'm not her brother.

391
00:31:32,431 --> 00:31:35,762
We stopped for a Coca-Cola,
which I thought was really cool.

392
00:31:35,806 --> 00:31:40,428
They had coke there and it was
the anxiety of how long it was taking.

393
00:31:42,140 --> 00:31:47,424
Minutes before she arrived
I was convinced it was finished.

394
00:31:47,681 --> 00:31:50,962
That I was gonna get arrested
and maybe beat up also

395
00:31:51,014 --> 00:31:53,254
because they were
not going to be happy about it.

396
00:31:54,765 --> 00:31:57,300
I remember going into like a waiting area.

397
00:31:57,640 --> 00:32:02,510
I'm speaking with a couple of people from
the home saying that he was in his room.

398
00:32:02,555 --> 00:32:05,387
He'd been locked in his room all day.
He wouldn't let anyone go in.

399
00:32:05,429 --> 00:32:08,877
Finally when I heard someone
knocking at the door and saying,

400
00:32:08,929 --> 00:32:13,174
"Hey, Nicholas, your sister is downstairs,

401
00:32:13,223 --> 00:32:15,426
er...she's waiting for you, she's there..."

402
00:32:17,055 --> 00:32:19,378
CAREY: I went downstairs
and into like a courtyard.

403
00:32:19,430 --> 00:32:22,264
There were some kids playing
like ball against a wall

404
00:32:22,305 --> 00:32:25,469
and looked up at the window
and told him,

405
00:32:25,514 --> 00:32:28,464
"I'm here, come here. I want to see you,
I want to hold you."

406
00:32:28,513 --> 00:32:32,174
I remember seeing him look out the window.

407
00:32:33,054 --> 00:32:37,214
I was sure that as soon as the sister
was gonna see me,

408
00:32:37,514 --> 00:32:40,595
she was going to say
"What the fuck is that?" You know.

409
00:32:40,639 --> 00:32:42,713
That's not...that's not Nicholas.

410
00:32:47,638 --> 00:32:49,629
I waited maybe 10 minutes.

411
00:32:51,554 --> 00:32:53,261
I knew I was about to lose everything.

412
00:32:53,804 --> 00:32:55,630
I knew I couldn't wait no more,

413
00:32:55,680 --> 00:32:57,172
that I couldn't go away,

414
00:32:57,221 --> 00:32:59,092
that I couldn't just disappear,

415
00:32:59,137 --> 00:33:01,508
so I opened the door and I went down.

416
00:33:06,429 --> 00:33:10,176
It was just this sense of immense relief.

417
00:33:11,139 --> 00:33:15,380
Just seeing, touching,
kissing, holding him.

418
00:33:16,762 --> 00:33:18,800
I said, "What the hell?" You know.

419
00:33:18,888 --> 00:33:21,671
He's here, we're here, I have him.

420
00:33:22,180 --> 00:33:25,592
She didn't even wait a second
or two seconds.

421
00:33:25,638 --> 00:33:27,877
She jump on me, she jump on me,

422
00:33:27,929 --> 00:33:29,552
she took me in her arms

423
00:33:29,595 --> 00:33:33,966
and she said, "Nicholas, oh, and you
were afraid I wouldn't recognise you.

424
00:33:34,010 --> 00:33:35,883
I would remember that nose."

425
00:33:35,927 --> 00:33:40,551
So I just... I remember touching his nose
and telling him, um,

426
00:33:40,596 --> 00:33:44,007
"I remember that nose,
you kind of look like your Uncle Pat."

427
00:33:44,719 --> 00:33:49,425
She said, "Don't worry," like she always say,
"everything is going to be fine.

428
00:33:49,470 --> 00:33:51,296
Everything is going to be perfect.

429
00:33:51,346 --> 00:33:53,253
I know it's you."

430
00:33:53,928 --> 00:33:56,676
He was just...just basically
told me he loved me,

431
00:33:56,719 --> 00:34:01,709
and he didn't say a whole lot
until all the people left.

432
00:34:04,345 --> 00:34:07,379
Only God know why she would
do something like that,

433
00:34:07,428 --> 00:34:15,249
but...but I know one thing for sure
is there was no other way.

434
00:34:15,302 --> 00:34:18,006
She came for me and she wanted me back.

435
00:34:20,510 --> 00:34:26,340
We went to the visit room
and she showed me dozens of pictures.

436
00:34:27,094 --> 00:34:29,167
Pictures, pictures, pictures.

437
00:34:29,803 --> 00:34:33,748
You remember, this was with Mom
at the, at the house we were living in

438
00:34:33,803 --> 00:34:35,796
before you, you went missing.

439
00:34:35,888 --> 00:34:39,501
Remember this was
when you were playing with Scotty.

440
00:34:39,553 --> 00:34:41,627
Remember this was...

441
00:34:43,219 --> 00:34:47,592
And he was like, "Jason looks the same,
Codey's gotten pretty big, huh?

442
00:34:47,802 --> 00:34:51,464
Mom, God, Mom looks exactly the same.
Has she put on weight?

443
00:34:52,594 --> 00:34:55,082
Wanted to know if Grandpa
was still an asshole,

444
00:34:55,136 --> 00:34:58,501
um, told me how much he loved Grandma
and he missed her.

445
00:34:59,884 --> 00:35:02,918
I remember seeing the tattoo,
the cross between his, you know,

446
00:35:02,968 --> 00:35:04,343
right here on his hand.

447
00:35:04,385 --> 00:35:07,549
I just kept thinking
how much he looks like Uncle Pat

448
00:35:07,594 --> 00:35:10,923
and how mom was going to be
really surprised how tall he was.

449
00:35:13,593 --> 00:35:16,213
She said that he looked very different,

450
00:35:16,260 --> 00:35:18,381
that he had, you know, grown up...

451
00:35:20,177 --> 00:35:22,629
..and erm...

452
00:35:22,676 --> 00:35:28,459
he's very quiet,
you know, kinda held back.

453
00:35:28,509 --> 00:35:31,341
He talked with a funny accent.

454
00:35:31,384 --> 00:35:35,462
But it was always a whisper and very quiet
like he was hiding from something.

455
00:35:39,384 --> 00:35:41,788
I mean, God,
look what he had been through.

456
00:35:41,925 --> 00:35:44,000
He wasn't the same person.

457
00:35:44,052 --> 00:35:47,049
He wasn't the same Nicholas
that disappeared four years before.

458
00:35:47,093 --> 00:35:50,209
He had been held and tortured
and God knows what else.

459
00:35:50,259 --> 00:35:52,332
He wasn't that same person.

460
00:35:58,759 --> 00:36:03,417
The judge in Linares wanted to make sure
that there was in fact some legal basis

461
00:36:03,468 --> 00:36:08,539
for Nicholas claiming to be er...
Carey Gibson's lost brother.

462
00:36:08,885 --> 00:36:16,173
So now the problem was that they
had the sister and the embassy official

463
00:36:16,218 --> 00:36:19,250
that were swearing
that I was Nicholas Barclay

464
00:36:19,300 --> 00:36:22,382
and there was the police
and the prosecutor

465
00:36:22,425 --> 00:36:25,375
and the judge
who were not convinced at all.

466
00:36:25,425 --> 00:36:27,795
The judge insisted on separate interviews

467
00:36:27,841 --> 00:36:35,166
and part of the evidence that was in those
interviews was a family photo album.

468
00:36:36,632 --> 00:36:39,880
And the judge said, "Listen,
the only way for you to prove

469
00:36:39,923 --> 00:36:43,042
that you're really Nicholas
is we got pictures here

470
00:36:43,092 --> 00:36:44,963
that you've never seen before.

471
00:36:48,258 --> 00:36:50,331
I'm gonna show you five of them."

472
00:36:51,716 --> 00:36:53,790
Number one, OK.

473
00:36:54,299 --> 00:36:55,957
Number two, OK.

474
00:36:56,007 --> 00:36:57,630
Number three, OK.

475
00:36:57,674 --> 00:36:59,379
Number four, OK.

476
00:36:59,423 --> 00:37:00,834
On the five one I made a mistake,

477
00:37:03,758 --> 00:37:05,131
but it was too late.

478
00:37:05,173 --> 00:37:07,544
She was already convinced
I was Nicholas Barclay.

479
00:37:08,258 --> 00:37:09,798
(Speaks Spanish)

480
00:37:14,342 --> 00:37:20,088
At that point I didn't see how I could
not document him as a US citizen.

481
00:37:24,673 --> 00:37:29,830
I would not have been able to do anything
if Carey didn't show me those pictures.

482
00:37:32,091 --> 00:37:36,249
They took picture of me,
with no hat, with nothing.

483
00:37:36,506 --> 00:37:39,042
Which was, you know, they saw my eyes.

484
00:37:39,965 --> 00:37:44,706
Erm, the constitution of the United States.
